items.name: Ext.data.operation.Create
items.text: Enacpsulates a create operation as performed by a Ext.data.proxy.Proxy. This class is instantiated by Ext.data.Store and Ext.data.Model and should not need to be instantiated in user code.

items.name: batch
items.text: The batch for this operation, if applicable

items.name: callback
items.text: Function to execute when operation completed.

items.name: records
items.text: Array of records.

items.name: operation
items.text: The Operation itself.

items.name: success
items.text: True when operation completed successfully.

items.name: id
items.text: The id of the operation.

items.name: internalCallback
items.text: A callback to run before the callback.

items.name: internalScope
items.text: Scope to run the internalCallback

items.name: params
items.text: Parameters to pass along with the request when performing the operation.

items.name: proxy
items.text: The proxy for this operation

items.name: recordCreator
items.text: Passed to the reader, see Ext.data.reader.Reader#read

items.name: records
items.text: The records associated with this operation. If this is a `read` operation, this will be null until data is returned from the Ext.data.proxy.Proxy.

items.name: request
items.text: The request for this operation.

items.name: response
items.text: The response for this operation.

items.name: resultSet
items.text: The ResultSet for this operation.

items.name: scope
items.text: Scope for the callback function.

items.name: synchronous
items.text: True if this Operation is to be executed synchronously. This property is inspected by a Ext.data.Batch to see if a series of Operations can be executed in parallel or not.

items.name: url
items.text: The url for this operation. Typically this will be provided by a proxy and not configured here.

items.name: abort
items.text: Aborts the processing of this operation on the proxy. This is only valid for proxies that make asynchronous requests.

items.name: allowWrite
items.text: Checks whether this operation should cause writing to occur.
Whether the operation should cause a write to occur.

items.name: constructor
items.text: Creates new Operation object.

items.name: config
items.text: (optional) Config object.

items.name: doProcess
items.text:
Process records in the operation after the response is successful and the result
set is parsed correctly. The base class implementation of this method is used by
"create" and "update" operations to allow the server response to update the client
side records.

items.name: resultSet
items.text: The result set

items.name: request
items.text: The request

items.name: response
items.text: The response

items.name: execute
items.text: Executes the operation on the configured proxy.
The request object

items.name: getError
items.text: Returns the error string or object that was set using setException
The error object

items.name: getRecords
items.text: Returns the Ext.data.Models associated with this operation. For read operations the records as set by the Ext.data.proxy.Proxy will be returned (returns null if the proxy has not yet set the records). For create, update, and destroy operations the operation's initially configured records will be returned, although the proxy may modify these records' data at some point after the operation is initialized.

items.name: hasException
items.text: Returns true if this Operation encountered an exception (see also getError)
True if there was an exception

items.name: hasOwnProperty
prop
items.text: The name of the property to test.

Returns true if object contains specified property; else
returns false.

items.name: isComplete
items.text: Returns true if the Operation has been completed
True if the Operation is complete

items.name: isPrototypeOf
prototype
items.text:
an object to be tested against each link in the prototype chain of the
*object* argument

items.name: object
items.text: the object whose prototype chain will be searched
Returns true if object is a prototype and false if not.

items.name: isRunning
items.text: Returns true if the Operation has been started but has not yet completed.
True if the Operation is currently running

items.name: isStarted
items.text: Returns true if the Operation has been started. Note that the Operation may have started AND completed, see isRunning to test if the Operation is currently running.
True if the Operation has started

items.name: propertyIsEnumerable
prop
items.text: The name of the property to test.

If the object does not have the specified property, this
method returns false.

items.text: Marks the Operation as completed.

items.name: setException
items.text: Marks the Operation as having experienced an exception. Can be supplied with an option error message/object.

items.name: error
items.text: (optional) error string/object

items.name: setStarted
items.text: Marks the Operation as started.

items.name: setSuccessful
items.text: Marks the Operation as successful.

items.name: complete
items.text: `true` to also mark this operation as being complete See setCompleted.

items.name: toLocaleString
items.text: Returns a string representing the object. This method is meant to be overridden by derived objects for locale-specific purposes. Objects toLocaleString returns the result of calling toString. This function is provided to give objects a generic toLocaleString method, even though not all may use it. Currently, only Array, Number, and Date override toLocaleString.
Object represented as a string.

items.name: toString

items.text: Object represented as a string.

items.name: valueOf
items.text: Returns the primitive value of the specified object. JavaScript calls the valueOf method to convert an object to a primitive value. You rarely need to invoke the valueOf method yourself; JavaScript automatically invokes it when encountering an object where a primitive value is expected. By default, the valueOf method is inherited by every object descended from Object. Every built- in core object overrides this method to return an appropriate value. If an object has no primitive value, valueOf returns the object itself, which is displayed as: [object Object] You can use valueOf within your own code to convert a built-in object into a primitive value. When you create a custom object, you can override `Object.valueOf` to call a custom method instead of the default Object method. You can create a function to be called in place of the default valueOf method. Your function must take no arguments. Suppose you have an object type `myNumberType` and you want to create a valueOf method for it. The following code assigns a user-defined function to the object's valueOf method: myNumberType.prototype.valueOf = new Function(functionText) With the preceding code in place, any time an object of type `myNumberType` is used in a context where it is to be represented as a primitive value, JavaScript automatically calls the function defined in the preceding code. An object's valueOf method is usually invoked by JavaScript, but you can invoke it yourself as follows: myNumber.valueOf() Note: Objects in string contexts convert via the toString method, which is different from String objects converting to string primitives using valueOf. All objects have a string conversion, if only `"[object type]"`. But many objects do not convert to number, boolean, or function.
Returns value of the object or the object itself.

items.name: wasSuccessful
items.text: Returns true if the Operation has completed and was successful
True if successful

items.name: commit
items.text:
This private object is used to save on memory allocation. This instance is used to
apply server record updates as part of a record commit performed by calling the
set() method on the record. See doProcess.

items.name: complete
items.text: The completion status of this Operation. Use isComplete.

items.name: constructor
error
items.text: The error object passed when setException was called. This could be any object or primitive.

items.name: exception
items.text: The exception status of this Operation. Use hasException and see getError.

items.name: foreignKeyDirection
items.text: This number is used by Ext.data.Batch#sort to order operations of the same type. This value is multipled by the "entity rank" (which is determined by foreign-key dependencies) to invert the direction of the sort based on the type of operation. Only Ext.data.operation.Destroy overrides this value.

items.name: order
items.text: This number is used by Ext.data.Batch#sort to order operations. Order of operations of the same type is determined by foreign-key dependencies. The array of operations is sorted by ascending (increasing) values of order.

items.name: prototype
items.text: Allows the addition of properties to all objects of type Object.

items.name: running
items.text: The run status of this Operation. Use isRunning.

items.name: started
items.text: The start status of this Operation. Use isStarted.

items.name: success
items.text: Whether the Operation was successful or not. This starts as undefined and is set to true or false by the Proxy that is executing the Operation. It is also set to false by setException. Use wasSuccessful to query success status.
